i. More notably, placed in this context, the book discusses the creative work and media personas of talented Colombian artists Shakira, Andrea Echeverri of Aterciopelados, and Carlos Vives. In her examination of the transnational figures and music that illuminate the recent shifts in the meanings attached to Colombian identity both in the United States and Latin America, Cepeda argues that music is a powerful arbitrator of memory and transnational identity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-SA 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aIdentity (Psychology) and mass media. 0aMusic tradezFloridazMiami. 0aMusicxSocial aspectszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aPopular musiczColombiaxHistory and criticism. 0aPopular musiczFloridazMiamixHistory and criticism. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Discrimination & Race Relations.2bisacsh  aColombian.  aImagiNation.  aMiami.  aMusical.  acrisis.  adynamics.  aeconomic.  aimmigration.  ametropolitan.  aongoing.  aoverview.  apolitical.  aprovides.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311070644440uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9780814716915.001.0001zOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814772904zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780814772904/original  a978-3-11-070644-4 New York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA